[
    {
        "content": "<p>Why does subtraction categorify so poorly?</p>",
        "id": 247601171,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627573281
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ive read a couple of things now where we want to view a ring or group as a decategorification of something or other, and it seems the generally-accepted solution—at least insofar as forming a grothendieck group/ring is a generally-accepted solution—is simply to add formal inverses</p>",
        "id": 247601331,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627573344
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>this strikes me as unsatisfying—i feel like if what you want is to categorify a ring or group, then the subtraction or inversion should themselves categorify?</p>",
        "id": 247601443,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627573401
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>idk</p>",
        "id": 247601444,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627573401
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what's going on here?</p>",
        "id": 247601453,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627573405
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Forming fibers or cofibers in a pointed category (and particularly a stable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-category) is often a reasonable categorification of \"subtraction\".</p>",
        "id": 247608095,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627576572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247608095\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Forming fibers or cofibers in a pointed category (and particularly a stable <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span>-category) is often a reasonable categorification of \"subtraction\".</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>how so?</p>",
        "id": 247626970,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627585490
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Well, for example, the Euler characteristic maps cofibers to subtraction: <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>χ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>χ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>−</mo><mi>χ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\chi(X/A) = \\chi(X) - \\chi(A)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">χ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 247629477,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627586791
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For another thing: consider a pointed category with pushouts. That lets us form coproducts:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ZkwMeb2b81Jr2GsdkAwQUYIi/image.png\">image.png</a> </p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/ZkwMeb2b81Jr2GsdkAwQUYIi/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/ZkwMeb2b81Jr2GsdkAwQUYIi/image.png\"></a></div><p>If we then compute the cofibre <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>∨</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y\\to X\\vee Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>, that's another pushout glued onto the first one:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/45QXZEuFnuLe5nAlVA7DD-RP/image.png\">image.png</a> </p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/45QXZEuFnuLe5nAlVA7DD-RP/image.png\" title=\"image.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/45QXZEuFnuLe5nAlVA7DD-RP/image.png\"></a></div><p>But since these are two pushouts stacked on top of each other, the outside square is also a pushout. We conclude that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>≅</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C\\cong X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, so the cofibre of the natural inclusion map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>∨</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y\\to X\\vee Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> is just <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 247635797,
        "sender_full_name": "Ian Coley",
        "timestamp": 1627589977
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>huhh</p>",
        "id": 247639718,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627592013
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>how are pushouts computed in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mo>∗</mo></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Set}_*</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Set</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.175696em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, say</p>",
        "id": 247639754,
        "sender_full_name": "sarahzrf",
        "timestamp": 1627592031
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They're just pushouts in Set, with the induced basepoint.</p>",
        "id": 247639874,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627592081
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>ooh, does the forgetful functor create connected colimits or sth</p>",
