    {
        "content": "<p>Cf: <a href=\"https://inquiryintoinquiry.com/2021/05/10/animated-logical-graphs-75/\">Animated Logical Graphs &bull; 75</a></p>\n<p>A couple months ago I was trying to come up with a good name for an operation dual to logical implication in a particular context, and what I got happened to be <em>subtraction</em>.  See the above blog post.  So maybe propositions as types would suggest a cat-analogue?</p>",
        "id": 247649966,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Awbrey",
        "timestamp": 1627598173
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I have heard of subtractions as co-implications in \"complement topoi\"<br>\nThey come up in more recent work on bi-intutionism such as this recent paper \"Pragmatic and dialogic interpretations of bi-intutionism\". <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bblfish/status/1413466013488799745\">see this recent tweet in a thread on dualities started by John Baez</a>. I am not sure if this is the same idea of subtraction that <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276072\">@sarahzrf</span> is looking for.</p>\n<div class=\"inline-preview-twitter\"><div class=\"twitter-tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/bblfish/status/1413466013488799745\"><img class=\"twitter-avatar\" src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/77b199c7e82b7b9c52e9d03926bbf1970d09fe5d/68747470733a2f2f7062732e7477696d672e636f6d2f70726f66696c655f696d616765732f313030343332363736313630383431373238312f486a786a533942585f6e6f726d616c2e6a7067\"></a><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/johngstell\">@johngstell</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez\">@johncarlosbaez</a> <a href=\"https://twitter.com/giuliasindoni\">@giuliasindoni</a> Ah yes, thanks.  A later paper:\n\"Pragmatic and dialogic interpretations of bi-intuitionism\" \nIn short: When both sides of the duality are combined so as not to collapse into first order logic, a logic of dialogue appears\n<a href=\"https://t.co/KflJ2HNSeB\">https://apcz.umk.pl/czasopisma/index.php/LLP/article/view/LLP.2014.011</a> <a href=\"https://t.co/AHJVosyvp5\">https://twitter.com/bblfish/status/1413466013488799745/photo/1</a></p><span>- The 🐟‍‍ BabelFish (@bblfish)</span><div class=\"twitter-image\"><a href=\"https://t.co/AHJVosyvp5\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/b643074b2a6afee69212e5493e870c0713d778ed/68747470733a2f2f7062732e7477696d672e636f6d2f6d656469612f4535326a6733415649414131554c432e706e673a6c61726765\"></a></div><div class=\"twitter-image\"><a href=\"https://t.co/AHJVosyvp5\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/0a42d118a34ed5eb99433d73e31f1f9fd939e3e9/68747470733a2f2f7062732e7477696d672e636f6d2f6d656469612f4535326a7a33345759414d724c6b7a2e706e673a7468756d62\"></a></div></div></div>",
        "id": 247669748,
        "sender_full_name": "Henry Story",
        "timestamp": 1627620168
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In particular from <a href=\"https://apcz.umk.pl/czasopisma/index.php/LLP/article/view/LLP.2014.011\">Pragmatic and dialogic interpretations of bi-intutionsm. Part I</a></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>It is very appropriate to ask such a question about bi-intuitionism: following Rauszer’s approach researchers in this area usually define bi- intuitionism by extending intuitionistic logic with the connective of subtraction C \\ D, to be read as “C excludes D”, which in algebraic terms is the left adjoint to disjunction in the same way as implication is the right adjoint to conjunction (see the rules in (1.1) below). This pair of adjunctions establishes a duality between the core minimal fragments of intuitionism and co-intuitionism, namely, intuitionistic conjunction and implication with a logical constant for validity, on one hand, and co- intuitionistic disjunction and subtraction with invalidity, on the other.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>(I could not find Part II last time I looked)</p>",
        "id": 247669971,
        "sender_full_name": "Henry Story",
        "timestamp": 1627620509
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Another context in which \"disjunction\" is a two-variable right adjoint is a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>∗</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\ast</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.46528em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∗</span></span></span></span>-autonomous category.</p>",
        "id": 247670405,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627621155
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"295756\">Ian Coley</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247635797\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If we then compute the cofibre <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>∨</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y\\to X\\vee Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>...</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why is this given a different name in a pointed category versus any category with a terminal object (where it's called a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/cokernel\">cokernel</a>)? It doesn't seem quite dual to the notion of fiber, at least morally, since the whole point of a fiber is that it extracts information over a <em>particular</em> global point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1 \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and that becomes a lot less meaningful in a pointed category where there is exactly one such morphism.</p>",
        "id": 247689461,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1627639787
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>my favourite categorification of subtraction (or, more generally, inverse operation of a monoid) is through compact closed categories.<br>\nexplicitly, if a monoid categorifies to a monoidal category, a group should categorify to a compact closed category.<br>\nin fact the property '<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a + b = c</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span></span></span></span> iff <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">a = c - b</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span></span></span></span>', which defines substraction, gets categorified to the adjunction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>⊗</mo><mi>b</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mo>≅</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>a</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>⊗</mo><msup><mi>b</mi><mo>∗</mo></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[a \\otimes b, c] \\cong [a, c \\otimes b^*]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">a</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">c</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">⊗</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.688696em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mbin mtight\">∗</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>. Or more simply, the unit and counit associated to the dual of an object categorify the properties <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>−</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">b-b=0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">−</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-b + b = 0</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 247690813,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1627640876
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>also the int construction fits into this picture, as a categorification of the group-completion (idk if this is the correct name) of a monoid</p>",
        "id": 247690925,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1627640940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If the left adjoint on + gives us subtraction, is there an adjoint that gives us division?</p>",
        "id": 247698919,
        "sender_full_name": "Henry Story",
        "timestamp": 1627646579
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is reminding me of the relation between a group and a torsor for the group: the torsor is where you get to do division (or subtraction) and that gets you back to the group. Example: in an affine space you can subtract one point from another, and this gives you an element of the translation group. </p>\n<p>Now I'm wondering about the connection to the basepoint discussion above: a group is a torsor with a basepoint (or, a torsor is a group that forgot its identity element). <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span></p>",
        "id": 247699717,
        "sender_full_name": "Simon Burton",
        "timestamp": 1627647080
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>One 'problem' with the int construction is that it doesn't work in the context of rig categories: if you perform int on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span>, you collapse everything.  See <a href=\"https://www.math.uni-hamburg.de/home/richter/crelle-aop.pdf\">Ring completion of rig categories</a> for how involved this gets.  If nothing else, everyone should read Thomason's wonderful  (and short - 4 pages)<a href=\"https://www.jstor.org/stable/2043425?origin=crossref\">Beware the Phony Multiplication on Quillen's <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathscr{A}^{-1}\\mathscr{A}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.22925em;\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">−</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathscr\" style=\"margin-right:0.22925em;\">A</span></span></span></span> </a>.</p>",
        "id": 247701801,
        "sender_full_name": "Jacques Carette",
        "timestamp": 1627648516
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277321\">Simon Burton</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247699717\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This is reminding me of the relation between a group and a torsor for the group: the torsor is where you get to do division (or subtraction) and that gets you back to the group. Example: in an affine space you can subtract one point from another, and this gives you an element of the translation group. </p>\n<p>Now I'm wondering about the connection to the basepoint discussion above: a group is a torsor with a basepoint (or, a torsor is a group that forgot its identity element). <span aria-label=\"thinking\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f914\" role=\"img\" title=\"thinking\">:thinking:</span></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Because you do not need constants to define a torsor in terms of a ternary operation, if you admit the empty torsor, then torsors are \"groups\" with possibly no identity  at all!</p>",
        "id": 247706594,
        "sender_full_name": "Cole Comfort",
        "timestamp": 1627651237
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"281126\">Henry Story</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247698919\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If the left adjoint on + gives us subtraction, is there an adjoint that gives us division?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>you need to use <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>×</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\times</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">×</span></span></span></span> instead</p>",
        "id": 247715126,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1627655220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Its the right adjoint to exponentiation</p>",
        "id": 247717007,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1627656183
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/1999/n10/5-10abs.html\">'Aspects of fractional exponent functors'</a></p>",
        "id": 247717208,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1627656291
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247717007\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Its the right adjoint to exponentiation</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"341237\">Fawzi Hreiki</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247717208\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"http://www.tac.mta.ca/tac/volumes/1999/n10/5-10abs.html\">'Aspects of fractional exponent functors'</a></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>But exponentiation is implication, sorta?</p>",
        "id": 247722627,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Awbrey",
        "timestamp": 1627658644
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247689461\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"295756\">Ian Coley</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247635797\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If we then compute the cofibre <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Y</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>∨</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Y\\to X\\vee Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∨</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>...</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Why is this given a different name in a pointed category versus any category with a terminal object (where it's called a <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/cokernel\">cokernel</a>)? It doesn't seem quite dual to the notion of fiber, at least morally, since the whole point of a fiber is that it extracts information over a <em>particular</em> global point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">1 \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>, and that becomes a lot less meaningful in a pointed category where there is exactly one such morphism.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I guess it really is a cokernel; I was just trying to draw out the un-stable version of Mike's point above mine.</p>",
        "id": 247724572,
        "sender_full_name": "Ian Coley",
        "timestamp": 1627659621
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then again, in <a href=\"https://oeis.org/wiki/Differential_Logic_and_Dynamic_Systems_%E2%80%A2_Overview\">differential logic</a>, which is basically differential geometry over GF(2), algebraic <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span></span></span></span> corresponds to logical <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{xor}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">xor</span></span></span></span></span> and set-theoretic <em>symmetric difference</em>, so <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>−</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+ = -</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.66666em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span></span></span></span> .</p>",
        "id": 247725619,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Awbrey",
        "timestamp": 1627660099
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"277473\">@Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span> The word cofiber isn't specific to a pointed category; it's just a different name for cokernel.  The word \"cofiber\" tends to be used in more topological and homotopy-theoretic contexts, while \"cokernel\" tends to be used in more additive contexts.  In contexts that are both homotopy-theoretic and additive, like spectra or chain complexes, it's a toss-up, and in chain complexes you also have a third word \"cone\" for the same thing.</p>",
        "id": 247735259,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627664526
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The same is true of \"fiber\" and \"kernel\".</p>",
        "id": 247735313,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627664566
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's true that fibers also exist in unpointed categories, where you have to choose a basepoint to take the fiber over.  But they are very interesting and useful in pointed categories, where they are the precise dual of a cofiber/cokernel.</p>",
        "id": 247735394,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627664616
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By duality, one might argue that in an unpointed category the appropriate notion of \"cofiber/cokernel\" would be a pushout along a (chosen!) map to the <em>initial</em> object.</p>",
        "id": 247735485,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1627664658
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Evidently we have a smörgåsbordism on offer ...</p>",
        "id": 247736198,
        "sender_full_name": "Jon Awbrey",
        "timestamp": 1627665017
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category.20theory/topic/subtraction/near/247735485\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>By duality, one might argue that in an unpointed category the appropriate notion of \"cofiber/cokernel\" would be a pushout along a (chosen!) map to the <em>initial</em> object.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I would indeed argue that it would be useful to have a terminological distinction here. Namely:<br>\n<em>kernel</em>: pullback along unique map from initial object<br>\n<em>fiber</em>: pullback along specified map from terminal object<br>\nand similarly for the dual concepts,<br>\n<em>cokernel</em>: pushout along unique map to the terminal object<br>\n<em>cofiber</em>: pushout along specified map to the initial object</p>",
        "id": 247794734,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1627722284
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That said, I can't think of (m)any common non-pointed categories where this notion of cofiber would be interesting, so the conflation that currently happens is harmless.</p>",
        "id": 247797085,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1627726546
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The category of rings is an interesting example of a non-pointed category whose initial object is not strict.</p>",
        "id": 247799561,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1627730891
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Cofibers of course then correspond to fibers over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>Spec</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{Spec}\\mathbb{Z}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.88333em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">Spec</span></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span></span></span></span>-points in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>AffSch</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\text{AffSch}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\">AffSch</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
